Java is a popular, object-oriented programming language that was first introduced by Sun Microsystems (now Oracle) in 1995.

It is used for developing various types of applications, such as web applications, mobile applications (Android apps), enterprise applications, and more. Java is designed to be platform-independent, which means that code written on a Java Virtual Machine (JVM) on one operating system can run on a JVM on another operating system.

The Java language is part of the Java Development Kit (JDK), which includes the Java compiler (javac), the Java runtime (java), and other tools for developing and deploying Java applications.

Here's a simple example of Java code:

```java
public class HelloWorld {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        System.out.println("Hello, World!");
    }
}
```

This code defines a class named `HelloWorld` with a `main` method, which is the entry point of a Java application. The `System.out.println` statement prints "Hello, World!" to the console.
